commit.message:
Added ACPI method for ThinkPad E490 GPU turn off 

Added ACPI method "\_SB_.PCI0.RP05.PEGP._OFF" to the script "turn_off_gpu.sh". That method successfully turns off the discrete AMD GPU of a Lenovo ThinkPad E490.

After turning off, discharge rate reported by powertop is about 4W lower.

GPU remains off after resuming from sleep.

Fix -Wframe-larger-than warning

Rename variable input to input_buffer and make it static.

Increase BUFFER_SIZE to fit _PRT packages

Current limit of 256B is not enought for \_SB_.PCI0._PRT on my laptop.
The limit of 1kiB is enough for me, but I have seen a machine where
BUFFER_SIZE of 1kiB is not enough. 4kiB ought to be enough for anybody.

commit.message:
Fix for 5.13+ kernels

Upstream commit d4455faccd6c ('proc: mandate ->proc_lseek
in "struct proc_ops"') made seek support for proc mandatory.

Not providing it will cause a null pointer exception for kernels
>=5.13.0

Signed-off-by: Alexander Wetzel <alexander@wetzel-home.de>

commit.message: Fix printk format for 64-bit computers (size_t was hardcoded to %u)

Update README

Considering that this is now (at least after ...) a fully
functional, general purpose ACPI call module, the
various reservations and referring to non-general
purpose tools are no longer appropriate.

Fix acpi_proc_read() not terminating properly

This caused a problem with e.g. `cat` producing garbled output
like: 0x2ealled

Here's why:
acpi_proc_read() is usually called multiple times in a row.
*off is supposed to be used by us to keep track of where we
are across those calls.
Once the user triggers a new read, *off will be 0 again.

Theoretically, we would need to be prepared to continue
reading from somewhere within the buffer on a second or
third call. But since ACPI calls don't tend to return a ton of data
and the target buffer appears to usually be kilobytes in size,
I think it is fair to gloss over this for now.

Make Makefile and dkms.conf use VERSION

PLUS: Add dev target

commit.message:
Fix memory leak of args

Args can potentially be allocated event when parse_acpi_args is returning
a NULL method pointer, so we end up with it being leaked when method
is NULL. Fix this by freeing args if it is non-null.

Signed-off-by: Colin Ian King <colin.king@canonical.com>
